review_text: We came across this place while walking around the old city. There was a bit of a lineup when we went in the evening. Food looked really good so, we decided to have dinner there. There are few tables, a lot of them actually, and there is an electronic wait list, very cool. There are not many options on the menu, just a few items. We ordered the shrimp and the pork options, dry and wet, respectively. We watched the food being made, very fresh and very quick. Both the dishes were excellent and tasted excellent, very tasty. Definitely a restaurant I would go back to.

excellent queue system, easy to navigate. queued and got a number, sat down and was served under 10 mins. suki was delicious, stir-fried with fresh cabbage and the dipping sauce is a must. this dish is unique, doesn't have a strong flavour but has a nice note of pepper and saltiness - not a dish for everyone but i certainly enjoyed this. pretty reasonable price too.

If you‚Äôve ever wondered how far humans will go for a bowl of sizzling suki yaki, welcome to Suki Changphuak, the legendary night-market stall sitting by the Chang Phuak Gate. Rumor has it this place has been firing up woks for decades The queue speaks Michelin vibes. The cook is a street-vendor-masterchef, and they run a fully computed cashier + ticket numbering system ‚Äî because chaos must be managed when hungry humans descend. We joined a line that looked like a pool of polar bears sensing food in the arctic summer. If you‚Äôre already starving, please don‚Äôt start here‚Äîhangry breakdowns may occur. ü§£ ‚è± Our waiting time: 45 minutes üéØ Our prize: Mixed Seafood and beef Suki Yaki ‚Äî smoky, savory, slightly charred noodles with juicy prawns, squid and veggies. Best with a hint of spice from the chilly dip Top tip: While waiting, grab snacks and beers from the neighboring stalls or treat yourself to a bualoy (sweet glutinous rice balls) from the vendor opposite. It makes the line-watching and noodle-counting more meaningful.

‚Ä¢ A famous Thai-style sukiyaki restaurant. The original branch can get very crowded, especially during peak hours. A good alternative is to visit another branch or order through a delivery app, the rider mentioned there‚Äôs even a special lane for delivery orders. ‚Ä¢ The overall taste is good, with the highlight being the quality of the meat and the smoky aroma from the pan-fried cooking style. ‚Ä¢ If you visit with normal expectations, it‚Äôs a 5-star experience, but if you come with high expectations, it might feel more like 3 stars.

This is one of my favorite restaurants that I always visit every time I come to Chiang Mai. However, this branch was a bit disappointing. I usually go to the Green Park branch the aroma from the pan there is much better, though the dipping sauce tastes the same. The boiled liver here was done perfectly, very delicious. I still like the restaurant overall, but next time I‚Äôll probably go back to the Green Park branch.

It‚Äôs a must-try if you want to have local street food in Chiang Mai. This one is the original brunch that has been open for over 30 years. The queue would be long so we recommend reserving via the app QueQ in advance. My favorite is always Dried Suki with beef (extra) that is perfectly cooked and aroma smell of smoke. Meat is seasoned well and tender while veggies are also cooked well and crispy. The price is so reasonable with great ingredients. You can add more toppings like extra-meat, veggies or glass noodle as you desire.

Prob most famous suki(was originally a hot pot but they do stir-fry style)in chiang mai. If there is a long waiting line i recommend to order to-go and find some place to enjoy it. I like dry stir-fry style suki with all the condiment.

It‚Äôs bustling with people tourist and locals alike + food courier guys. Our hotel was nearby and while we were going to the pharmacy we passed by the night market. We were curious of the long queue and decided to try this one üòã perfect for a chilly, rainy night. This was one of my favorite dish so far during my Thailand trip - I‚Äôm not a fan of spicy food. It‚Äôs a good thing that they‚Äôre providing a separate spicy condiment as to how you want your soup taste like. It‚Äôs nice to have a little kick by putting in some. üôÇ very tasty and pair up with Lookchin or Chang Beer!! üçª
Waited for 2hrs ..... BUT it's really good. Not sure if I would wait for another 2 hrs next time. But food is really good and service is great too.

Great street food!! The hype is definitely real on this place. It is extremely busy every day of the week at every time they open up. So be prepared to wait at least 10-20 minutes for your order. But it is well worth it. The stir fried dish with pork is absolutely delicious and very cheap as well. Very tasty and very filling. Not too spicy but amazing in flavour. They got the whole system figured out with a wel organised line of people creating these great dishes. Eating there or take away are both amazing options. First order your dish and tell them if you want to be seated on the market or take it with you to eat wherever. Then watch how they go to work. An amazing street food vendor with the most delicious stir fry.

It opens at 5:30 pm. When I arrived around 5:30 pm the place had already many people. The ordering system is nothing I've seen at the food stall and it's very efficient! The food was amazing, especially the sauce. I loved the food and experience here.

Overall: 3/7 Truly do not understand the hype for this. It has an insane line and it‚Äôs really not worth it. -1 for wait time Tastes like a random mix of everything thrown in together. Because that‚Äôs what it is. There‚Äôs not even a secret sauce or soup involved. Also it comes with a very minimal serving of noodles as a base - most of the contents are veggies. Would recommend getting the soup over the dry pot. It‚Äôs the same thing, except the soup one gives you an extra bag of soup.

super good the stir fried glass noodle! i didn‚Äôt plan to dine here but then i smell something good from this stall, then i gave it a try, turned out super good! 60 THB got this and everything in the bowl is well coated with egg that gave its fragrance

This restaurant is definitely a must-visit when traveling in this province. It can get a little busy, but the management is well organized, with quick service and very generous portions. Ordering is convenient through a QR code system on your phone. The food is delicious, and I would definitely come back again on my next visit!

Walked passed by and saw a long queue so waited to have dine in. It was around 8-9pm and had about 40 teams to wait ‚Ä¶and was about more than an hour waiting time. Decided to get a take away instead, still waited about half an hour. It was worth waiting since I got to try the food. Delicious noodle and cabbages. Understand why so many people lined up to eat this dish. The following day I ordered another soup dishes through Grab. Food five stars Personally don‚Äôt like lining up for long time while there were so many cars driving besides to get in to a carpark.. is not my thing so four stars. Highly recommend: use Grab Order
10/10 recommend, The best SUKI in town, can book via Queq - no wait, But quite HOT you need to bring your personal fan üî• AROI MAKMAK

Dinner out turned into a marathon! Waiting for ages‚Äî2 hours after 68 people, then another 20 minutes after ordering. But finally, I got my Seafood Stir-fried Suki and Pork Stir-fried Suki. The glass noodles were slick, the Suki sauce with its umami and sweet veggie taste was a bit oily, and that wok aroma? Nice touch! Overall, the taste is amazing, definitely worth trying, but seriously, the wait time is insane!

Stumbled upon this stall while walking around the market. Many patrons consist of both tourists and locals. Took a number from the counter and waited to be called. Didn't need to wait long, number was called within 5 minutes, ordered a dry and a soupy one, paid and was appointed to a table. Food were quickly served and we preferred the dry one. Glass noodles were delicious, got wok-hey (if you know, you know). Reasonably priced and give it a try if you visiting ChiangMai. üòâ

The hygiene was terrible. We went to that night market yesterday to try some snacks, and one of the stalls was selling grilled sausages. We bought some, but when eating them, we found a hair inside ‚Äî it looked like a pubic hair. It was really disgusting, and even today we still feel nauseous thinking about it. The food didn‚Äôt taste good either.‚Ä¶‚Ä¶

The food is fantastic, with vegetables that have a wonderfully crispy texture and an amazing aroma. I highly recommend trying the sukiyaki with rice‚Äîit‚Äôs a unique dish I haven‚Äôt seen anywhere else, and it‚Äôs absolutely worth it. The atmosphere is somewhat crowded and could use a bit of cleaning, but it‚Äôs understandable for a street food spot. Overall, it‚Äôs a great place for delicious meals! ü§©üëçüèª

Bad service! I ordered food 20.30pm got #65 and staff told me take away queue is #60 now. Then i saw one take away bag on the table but the queue still 61. I looked at staff and no one making any order around 20.50 pm. Suddenly one of staff looked at me and grabbed the order that i have seen like almost 10 mins before #65 meanwhile number is still #61 Almost 21.00 pm. No changing the number!! Long waiting!! First time trying this restaurant with terrible service

Amazing, we saw the line of people waiting before we even knew what they were serving. We had a pork stir fry with noodles and a pork seafood mix stir fry with noodles. Delicious, each bowl freshly made.

Ordered stir fried suki with extra vegetables. It tasted very good, but I feel it's kinda similar to suki I tried in Bangkok. So I'm not sure why it's very famous. I came very early at 5pm (it opens at 5:30pm) so I was one of the first customer of the day, but I still needed to wait for around 30mins since they were still preparing the shop

This is a bustling food stall on the street. Simple menu, no need for words, just need to point. It opens at 530 pm, and I arrived shortly thereafter. I ordered the chicken stir fry with extra veggies and extra noodles. My wait time was ~ 10 minutes. Well worth the wait, and I savored every bite when I got back to my residence.

Absolutely worth the wait in line! The flavors were so unique, with that delicious hint of smokiness from the hot pan. We loved both the stir-fried and soup-style suki‚Äîso satisfying! Pro tip: grab a fresh fruit smoothie from the shop nearby to enjoy with your meal.

It‚Äôs the most famous Suki yaki restaurant in Chiang mai. There was a long queue even in the weekdays. I arrived at 6 PM ,I waited for about 45min. I ordered seafood dry suki yaki, it‚Äôs so delicious and smells like burnt. The bowl is quite big, the price is reasonable.

The famous and original creator of dry suki ! Or so I have been told üòÖ. We pass by often as we usually dine at the other famous cowboy lady braised pork leg just next door. Queues are always long here so do go later for dinner so you don't have to wait so long. I am no fan of thai suki as I had horrible tasting ones and decided not to order this dish again. Lo and behold , we went for late dinner and there was a short queue so wife decided to eat here. I had dry suki with pork while wife had seafood and both the dishes were delicious. What a difference in flavour. Thoroughly enjoyable. They have a queue system so get your number and wait for them to call you. You can QR their menu to order. Parking : Kerbside only

The famous sukiyaki restaurant in Chiangmai is popular among both tourists and locals. Since there were many customers waiting for food, I decided to get food delivery, which had a very reasonable delivery fee. The food itself is quite nice with a delicious sauce. However, I ordered sukiyaki with soup, so the sauce wasn't balanced and got diluted. I recommend ordering it without the soup.

I came here at 5:15 PM and there was already a long queue. So if you want to eat at the store, be ready to wait a bit. Customer process: _ Get the queue number at cashier table _ Look at the screen to see what number is called to be seated _ Once it‚Äôs your turn, you‚Äôll go to the cashier table again to order, cashier will then tell you a table number to sit. _ Finish eating, go back to cashier to pay. Store process: _ There are 2 stations in charged of cooking fried Thai Suki. 1 station is in charged of cooking Thai Suki soup. Hence, you can tell fried Suki is more popular and preferred by customers. _ If you order Thai Suki soup to take home, the soup will be separated in different bag so that your noodle and veggies won‚Äôt be soggy. _ Chefs cook per order per dish, that‚Äôs why it takes a long time to wait for your food. Food overall is good, yet considering the waiting time (~1 hour), there should be other better options to eat and save time. Still, you should try here at least once!

Suki Chang Phuak is a renowned spot at the Chang Phuak Gate Night Market in Chiang Mai, Thailand, specializing in a Thai-style hot pot dish. Despite being referred to as ‚Äúsuki,‚Äù this dish is more reminiscent of a Chinese hot pot. Ingredients like meats, vegetables, and glass noodles are stir-fried or boiled together, seasoned with a house-made sauce. Customers often rave about the stir-fried suki, which is cooked on a hot iron griddle, giving it a lightly smoky flavor and retaining the crunch of the vegetables. The dish is served with extra sauce, allowing diners to customize the flavor to their taste. Besides the suki stall, the Chang Phuak Gate Night Market is home to various other beloved stalls, including options for grilled mini-pork balls, roast duck, and traditional Thai desserts like rice dumplings in coconut milk. This market is highly recommended for affordable, delicious local cuisine.

I regret giving the rider a tip with a card in advance. I waited in front of the accommodation and the rider came to another entrance and left it in front of the door. After the delivery was completed, I did not receive it and contacted the rider but he did not answer!! If he had told me that he would leave it at the front door, there would have been no problem. Why did he not answer me?? Very unpleasant and frustrating --;;; The taste is okay. I ordered seafood, but there was a lot of meat üòü

There is a queue when I visited on Friday around 7.30pm. Take a queue number from the counter and wait for the screen to show yours. It was pretty fast and I got a seat after 15-20min. Ordered stir fried glass noodles with seafood, the dish had wok hey and they gave plenty of prawns and squid!

Queued for a while (for takeaway as that Q was shorter) and tbh it wasn‚Äôt worth it. It was just ok. I went for the fried mixed suki and whilst it tasted good, I really didn‚Äôt understand the hype. Portion was also small. There are much better food options in the market such as the pork leg and duck stand.

Upon reaching here, do not be confused by a line forming. You need to obtain a queue number at the counter. Thereafter, you will have to wait for your number to be called. While waiting, you can watch the cook skilfully toss cabbage, glass noodles, and meat in the wok. Once the number is called, head to the counter to place your order. I noticed for locals they are given a QR code to place your order. Tourists on the other hand have to order at the counter. You choose between a stir fry option or a soup option. You then have to pick your ingredient, choosing from chicken, pork, seafood, a mix or mushrooms. Prices go for ‡∏ø55 to 65. Thereafter, a table is allocated to you. To give some perspective on the queue situation. I arrived at around 7 and had to wait around for an hour for my number to be called. Thereafter, I had to wait for around 15 minutes for my food. I got the stir fry mixed (‡∏ø65) and really enjoyed the flavour from the wok. The cabbage is crunchy and the meat is tender. I would recommend this dish and also coming earlier.

Amazing how they stir fried the veggies and meat this well, has the super nice smell of wok (thai style). Portions are great, very fulfilling for the price 50-60 baht. Suki sauce is not too spicy and very mellow, very tasty, with good parsley side taste. Totally recommend this place despite quite a long line.

Honestly didn‚Äôt have high expectations but it was THE BEST in Thailand. I would recommend taking out because the que for dine in is VERY LONG. The que for take out is quite short in contrary. DEFINITELY check out the pork option. Try the fried option. Also go for extra noodle and extra veggie. I stg you can‚Äôt stop digging in. I had it twice during my stay in Chiang Mai and still think about it to this day. Please make a detour if you‚Äôre not around the area. You won‚Äôt regret it.
This street vendor has the best sukiyaki!! Expect to wait anywhere from 5mins - 1hr for this amazing food! Definitely worth it! One of our favorite vendors in Old City! Highly recommend!

What is this feeling so sudden and new? 59B for pork Suki, I don‚Äôt even know what Suki is, I just saw a bunch of people waiting so I ordered one too. I ordered the soupy one, the pork is super tender I don‚Äôt know how they did that, and the spicy sauce is so yummy! And the vegetable I love it all. This is a very chiang mai experience where I ate at a street stall ride beside the super heavy traffic during dusk. My soup must be adding a lot of carbon monoxide ü§£ I would still come again if had the chance, next time I will order the dry one.

If you're a Thai suki lover, this is the place to be! Suki Changphuak is one of my all-time favorite sukis. Great taste, fresh veggies, and perfectly cooked pork make this dish outstanding. Plus, the price is affordable. The restaurant is a local street food spot, and you can eat there until late at night. I've been here a few times after a night of drinking. Sometimes, there can be a long queue as well.

Good food. Is it worth the long wait? Yes and no. The dry version is more delicious than the soup version, and also prefer the pork (they have chicken and beef options as well). They cook it on demand, so it's hot and comforting when eaten. For the queue, make sure to get a number from the counter. And once the number is displayed, order from the counter. We waited for 30 min for our queue number to pop. The food is good, but not sure if it's that good for the long queue. Would recommend it still for those who want to try.

Way too disappointedüôÅ, Since I am a real fan of this sukiyaki street food shop for mote than 10 years. However, this time the cooking method was changed (too much soup water, veg not fresh not crispy) and taste is not that impressive anymore. Very disappointed, and not crave for it anymore. Next time I will check it out, in case the taste is back on track, I will markup the stars.

Delicious stir fried suki and worth the hype. We got there at 5pm on a Monday in early Feb and there were no queues - it was empty. The sun was up and it was so hot as there was no shade. Definitely bring an umbrella if eating at this time. We tried the stir fried pork and chicken as most reviews said that was better, and it did not disappoint! Eat with the sauce poured into the dish and enjoyüëåcosted 50 baht per plate. Cowboy hat lady pork rice is also good at this small night market.

This restaurant is a renowned Suki restaurant in the heart of Chiang Mai city. The taste of the food is great, but expect a lot of long queue. However you can book via QueQ application but still 1 hr wait. For 1st time experience it is okay but maybe not worth the second visit. All the Suki taste the same the veggies are crisp and noodle is super soft. ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê Suki fried Beef ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê Suki fried Pork ‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê‚≠ê Suki fried seafood

The place for Thai style Sukiyaki or Suki. There are two version of these dish, the original one with broth and dry version of Suki. The dish mainly made of grass-noodle, vegetable and variety of meat on your choice. Signature of this dish is to eat with Suki sauce, Suki Chang Phuek making their own signature sauce. The broth is really nice very tasty and delicious. The taste sweet from the broth and a little spicy from sauce, it create rich and flavored taste. They offers pork, beef, fish, seafood, vegetarian and mixing all. Their Suki is well cooked, it's really good and healthy food.

We had both the soup and stir-fry. Stir-fry was better. I recommend to put the sauce in both meals. The staff confirmed that‚Äôs how it‚Äôs supposed to be eaten. You first need to go to the cashier, you‚Äôll get a pager and it will ring when a table is free (25min in our case). There you order, sit down and they will bring you the meal (extra 10-15min for us). For chicken stirfry, chicken soup and water we paid 90 ü¶á. When we waited we went to the stall in the third pic and I believe you should too. The chicken there was at least as good as the meals here but there were no people at all. Plus the lady was super nice and let us taste everything before ordering.

This place lives up to the hype, I must say! We waited in e queue approx 30mins but worth it!! The queue system is pretty straightforward, just walk up to the counter to pick up your number then wait for them to call.

Best food in Chiang Mai! Loved it, but you have to get a number first before ordering. Waited the first time for 40 min, the next time got the app (where you can get the ticket too), then you can time the waiting time better!

Stir fried Suki tastes so good. Really like the crunchiness of Chinese cabbage and the juicy while tendered pork. Overall is very impress, but after 1hour passed we both feel very thirsty. I‚Äôm pretty sure they put a great amount of MSG in food. Btw, worthy to try if you have never.
I personally think this one is overhype, its good but not too special I would recommend to get this on other branch, as this took me 1 hour waiting for 1 person to sit

Very tasty stir fry beef with cabbage, good wokhei. Added broth as side and it was also very tasty. Probably not mind-blowing enough to be worth the 40minute wait though, available on via delivery apps (though with slight markup THB 85 instead of THB 69), and just as good / piping hot since it's pretty near Nimman / eat in comfort and aircon of hotel.

Highly recommended!! It gets a perfect 10 out of 10. I love it Worth the money, but prepare to wait quite a while unless you book ahead of time via the QueQ app. The soup itself is fantastic. Sukiyaki sauce is also tasty. My advice is to specify "cooked veggies" for the soft texture of the vegetables that I love.

The first meal I had when I came back to Chiang Mai. This shop is very famous and popular, many influencers have visited and recommended here, such as Mark Wiens. The food is good but pricier than other suki places. The waiting time could be long, you need to get the tickets first and wait for a while before you can place your orders. The services are good and it‚Äôs an unforgettable experience to eat on the street at night time.

The food was ok. I opted for a takeaway as it was quicker, I waited around 25 mins. I don't think it's worth waiting 1-2 hours for a seat. I just didn't understand what was so special about the food (sorry) especially as there are so many amazing places to eat in the area.

Went there at about 515, got a queue number, waited about an hour! Though it was a long queue, but definitely worth it! We ordered both the soup and dry one, since it was our first time. Personally prefer the dry one as it's more fragrant and matches better with the sauce they provide. Do drop by if you have the time, try to be really early. Our number was 30 and by the time we entered, the queue has ballooned to 150.

It‚Äôs one of the most iconic street food market in Chiangmai. Located just opposite the Changpueuk. There are many options available for the Thai suki here. They have all kind of meats and also have the vegetarian option available. This time I have try the sterfry pork. You can have added egg , veggies, pork, beef or seafood. Please noted that there is a queue to take at the counter. Both for take away and dine in. Do try :) and enjoy !

Easily the best meal I had in Thailand. I can‚Äôt believe how delicious this food is. Never had anything like it. I‚Äôm not sure what people are talking about in regards to the staff being slow or rude, but I can confirm that those reviews are wrong because they were nice, accommodating and perfect. This place deserves recognition. I recommend the stir fried pork suki. I‚Äôll be trying to recreate this at home forever. 6/5 if I could

Really tasty Thai Suki. I had the dry mixed meat Suki with extra meat. Portion was ok if not overly generous. The taste was subtle but tasty, a smokiness to it. Service is efficient, it‚Äôs crazy busy and you take a numbered ticket to queue. I got there at around 5:30pm and waited around 80 mins to be seated. I expect later comers would be there most of the evening waiting.

Great price! Been here twice so far and both times have been good, but got to know the rules, you take a table only after you‚Äôve ordered, to place your order go to the cashier and get a number, wait for your number to be called so that you can place your order ü§§

Really good, fresh and crunchy suki. They are making bowl after bowl, so your dish comes fresh and piping hot. There‚Äôs usually quite a line up though, so expect to wait at least 30 minutes. Worth the wait though, and don‚Äôt forget the sauce! Adds a big kick of flavour. Check out our channel for a full review of our experience: Hungry Two Travel.

Yummy food, comforting. It‚Äôs located in a small night market. You‚Äôll see a lot of people queuing around the store but they might be waiting for a seat for dining in. Go straight to the counter to order and pay to get a queue number. We didn‚Äôt have to wait that long, maybe 15mins, there were ~12 people ahead of us. They seem to prepare each sukiyaki individually on the wok, but I may be wrong. The dry version comes with sauce to mix everything in - it‚Äôs a little spicy - which is great for people like me who can‚Äôt handle too much heat anyway. Also ordered it through delivery once and everything arrived as expected It‚Äôs a small portion by western standards. Comes with meat/vegetable of your choice, lettuce, glass noodles and egg (stir fried and mixed in).

I randomly passed by this place, and the smell was incredible. I didn‚Äôt even want to have dinner but suddenly I had to. I had the beef stir fry sukiyaki and it was so so SO good. Best food I had in Chiang mai. I would like to have it again tomorrow. And the day after tomorrow. The photo doesn‚Äôt make it justice. Oh and it was only 65baht! I had food after 9pm so there was no queue!
We had the fry up and not the soup. Was super tasty and worth the 20min wait. Long waiting lines are to be expected but they have a really good number drawing system in place that helps a lot.

One of the best sukiyaki in Chiang Mai! Worth to wait for the queue and everyone who stay close to the restaurant can use the app call ‚ÄúQueQ‚Äù for reserve a queue. Around that area have many popular food for the one who waiting for the queue such as grilled pork ball, fruit smoothies, Mala skewer, and etc. This sukiyaki branch also have some parking space behind the building close to the place and the fee for van is 20 baht and for smaller car just only 15 baht!

Very delicious! I‚Äôm a sukiyaki lover and this place delivers not just a tasty one but also a new concept to sukiyaki that can hardly be found anywhere. Usually, sukiyaki is plain, tasteless, and full with some hard-to-eat veggies on the plate. However, seems like this Changphuak suki has selected fine vegetable part that is easy to eat, and cooked to its crispiness, so people could enjoy and eat comfortably. It doesn‚Äôt feel like you would have a to eat a whole plate of vegetables, it is as flavorful and easy to eat as that. Love how they take order and arrange queues very fast, even though there are a lot of people each night, but they seem to take care very well. I came back twice during my 5 night stay at Chiangmai. This is probably one of the best sukiyaki shop in Thailand.

Ordered the pork stir fry suki. It came with various vegetables and glass noodles. They are quite well flavored but I found that it's too "wet" for stir fry dishes but the amount of pork given is quite generous. There's queue to get a seat and the wait for the food to come out is quite long. Also, there's no English menu when they asked me to scan the QR code to order so I had to approach the staff directly. Overall, a pretty good dish but it's not special.

This thai suki store is always super packed and has a long line. I came i‚Äôm here at 5pm and got a queue ticket and finally got a food on the table at 6pm. It‚Äôs pretty good, but I have had a better thai suki without waiting this much nearby CMU, so i don‚Äôt think it‚Äôs worth waiting for an hour here.

It's a famous food stall for suki, located along the moat that surrounds the old town, and many other food stalls nearby. There is no parking lot, so it is better to go by Songthaew or Tuk Tuk. We recommend that you go there early to avoid waiting for a long time. First, go to the cashier and pick up the waiting caller. The specialty suki comes in two types, with and without soup, but personally, I prefer the one without soup, where the taste is directly felt. Be sure to put the attached suki sauce on a plate and stir well before eating. If the taste isn't enough, ask the clerk for the suki sauce and add it.
Stir fry was tasty and we were fine. A lot of people waited in the line. We waited about 20 min to order but it was worth it. It

This isn't just suki yaki, it's an experience ‚ú® you have to get a ticket first from the counter then wit in line until your number is called. then place the order. the whole experience is fun and the anticipation whilst waiting for the food serves to enhance its flavour ü§û I did get stomach cramps next day but it was worth it (msg,!)‚Äã

Great Suki! Fresh veggies, tender meats, yummy sauce! I tried both dried and soupy ones, both of then are good. Generous portion, reasonable price. Note: Go early .. this place already pack by the time they open at 6pm.

A famous suki place where people who come to Chiangmai want to visit. It's good as reviews said. But I feel that I can find this taste in Bangkok as well so it might not worth queuing this long. And don't order home, it won't be as good. If you wanna try, suggest to get the queue from QueQ in advance to reduce waiting time. Don't forget to order extra - the portion is not very big.

Best suki in Chiangmai. Plenty of vegetable and noodles were nice and chewy. Has a very long wait time so best you book on the app (can click book once you are in range but range goes quite a few of kilometers out) before getting here so you can spend time elsewhere before your queue arrives. Booking can be made through the QueQ app.

Something you don't commonly find within the streets and this is proven by the super long queue. So how to overcome this to kill time? Take a queue number and walk over for an hour's massage (can't remember the shop but is just opposite the street, one of the better massages if you like strength and point ) Back to the food, a very easy and healthy dish, that anyone will like for a light dinner or supper.
The best Thai style sukiyaki.üëçüèª They make look easy but test delicious!. I recommended the fried one with everything and the soup with everting so good. 40-70THB/order
Good taste and very cheap price

The stirfried dish was great! Much preferred the pork to the beef. The pork slices were juicy and tender, and simply generous. Add mushrooms for another 10baht which was totally worth it! The portion can be quite small for a hungry man so make this the first stop of your dinner hunt. The flavours were appetising and makes you crave for more. Pro tip: Ignore the queue and go straight to the cashier counter. Say the number of people you have in your group and get a beeping device. That is how you join the (electronic) queue. When it's your turn to be seated, the device will beep and you simply go back to the same counter to place your order and be seated.

Very famous and long queue stir fried Suki, which is stir fried mung bean noodle with vegetables and choice of meat. I chose beef, it was pretty good! It has an outstanding wok hei smell, vegetables are crispy, meat given is big and soft. I have to wait around 40 minutes for table and 20 minutes for food. If you arrived at this place, go straight and ask for queue. Then you can scan the QR code to order when it's your queue. Atmosphere is on the street (street food).

A famous sukiyaki ( glass noodle stir fried or with soup ) you can select meat ie pork,beef, seafood. I recommend stir fried with any meat you like. 1 serve (as shown in photo => special portion) mixed with meat, glass noodle, mixed veggie&sauce, you can add sauce that serve with but a bit spice.
The best stirred fried suki in my life. Nothing can beat the crispy of veggie and the smell of it. If you come to Chaing Mai and you miss this restaurant you will regret.

Took queue # and was told have to wait for 30mins. Was abt 20 people ahead of me. Once my # being called, order at counter and make payment. Cashier suggested the dried version is tastier. The cashier will tell u where to sit. Then wait for another 10-15mins, food is served. Cost 65 bhat. Overall was alright though I found some vegetables not cooked and bland. (They did not mix well) saw the way the team washed their bowls. U won‚Äôt want to know
Great taste as always, portion is good too.
Thai style Suki that comes in decent size, tasty, and full filling meal. They specialized in dry type Suki. The queue can be long but worth the wait.

The best Thai sukiyaki in CNX, or even in Thailand for me. Process to order for dine in 1. Pick up the queue device at the cashier 2. Wait for device beeping 3. Get the assigned number table from the cashiee 4. Write the order on the paper at the table 5. Send order to the cashier 6. Waiting for your food 7. Enjoy your meal 8. Go to pay at the cashier

Popular suki in CNX This location have many restaurants . This place is Chinese destination for street food at CNX Good taste Long queue but can order via food delivery Today I choose dry type that I prefer more than soup type. Spicy Sauces is signature. Online payment is available
Tasty Thai style fried suki, sauce was amazing, for me the fried-dry type was too much oiled, but the soup type was better and healthier. The queue always long.
Very good food at the night market! There is a bit of a queue but it moves pretty fast. It was fun to see the chefs cooking as well!
Salted rice crispy pork topped is very good. The marinate is somewhat too strong, it gave a weird mouthfeel.
One of best 65 baht will get you - a super tasty stir fried goodness mix of cabbage, meats and seafood.
Expect a long wait, and you‚Äôll need to write down the order in thai, but the suki is very delicious and reasonably priced (60 baht for a big one).
Meh not sure why people like this food i tried the stir fry and the soup even got recommended selections by the staff. It wasnt bad it was just meh. I dont get the popularity.
Long line with an hours wait. Additional shrimp is small for 20 baht (see pictures of 2 shrimps)

A good typical Asian ‚Äústreet food‚Äù market with several vendors each with wide choice to eat or drink. Prices reasonable and tables and plastic stools for eating in. Beers also available. The smoke, smells and sounds make it a great place for a dinner out!

Pros: This place is insane!!! It is so good! This is a Japanese inspired Thai dish made with a secret sauce. One of the best meals I‚Äôve had in Thailand. The food is fresh and is cooked fresh right in front of you. The flavor is rich and mouth watering. The pork is juicy and delicious. Price at 50‡∏ø. Seriously worth making a trip across town to enjoy this amazing street food stall. 5/5 all the way! Cons: You won‚Äôt be able to find this pretty much anywhere else!

An extremely awful experience, u have to wait for the queue for at least 3 hours. The service is like a hell, not organized at all, and the food is just like a forecourt. Don't waste your time here. However, u can come here at lunch time, then you can get your order at dinnertime. Good luck.

Located in Chang puak gate‚Äôs night market and famous for its suki. Waited around 20 minutes to dine in(actually to use outside table) but seems to take less if you just to go and use another table besides. Taste was awesome, totally worth waiting and visiting !! Ordered fried seafood this time but will visit here again to try soup version!! Was very good.
Very fresh ingredients. Not impressed at the first try but kept thinking about it days after. Will come again next time in Chiang Mai.
Had a long long long queue. But worth the wait . Nice Suki cooked on the spot .

One of the best suki I've ever had! Recommended the fried one with everything. You can try suki with soup, fried suki and noodle dishes. Open at night, crowded during early night for dinner time, but it's worth the wait. THB50-70/person
Tasty dried Suki beef, highly recommended dried one over soup. I had to wait around 20 minutes, but worth the wait
Street food. Cheap. Flavorful. Must-try food at Chiang Mai
Stir fried Suki is great! The pork was tender. The dish had great flavour overall.

Took the dry version with pork. That was so freaking good! we were 3 and all want to come back. What I like with that plate is that there is plenty of veggies and you don't feel like it. Highly recommend it.
There's always a long line. The food is fairly at a low price. Just come here and enjoy the atmosphere. Maybe I will come again
The best Suki in my entire life! ‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è‚ù§Ô∏è

I tried the Suki Haeng Moo (stir fried pork) and I loved it. It feels a bit healthier than other options around as there are lots of veggies on it. You'll probably have to wait a bit but its worth it. Portions are not very big so its ideal as a starter. Kapunkap!
No matter how long the queue is, it will be delicious. I come to Chiang Mai every time I have to eat crispy vegetables, fresh, not too oily. Every menu is delicious.
Tasty, but long waiting queue. Order for mixed (pork + seafood) for THB65 Worth the wait
My friend took me here. I like the food, so happy. Food is really good.
Amazing Suki, had the pork, mixed and seafood all perfectly cooked. Top tip, get a seat ticket before queuing
Try some Seafood taste OK , nothing special . Can eat :) but waiting more then 1 Hour !!!! Some people like to wait üññüèº

This is one of the frenzy caused by YouTube hype. The foods are deemed to be tasty but not worth the long wait like 40-50 min or even longer. After noticing the dish washing area with 4-5 buckets of water I decided to take the foods out. Well...the plastic container should be cleaner and safer.....
Amazing! Worth waiting üíï we ordered the stir fried dish witch chicken, and another with pork. Around 50-60 thb
Nice suki, I ordered both the stir-fry & soup style, both were good but I feel that the soup version was better. The sauce that they served to go with the suki was amazing.
Very popular place for Suki. Waiting time was not too long. Taste wise was okay but it was very rushed, the vegetable were still uncooked. Not sure why the hype
The best Original Version of 1by1 cooking !! Coca -Suki Veg Fries. Very Delicious with beef/pork/fish/seafood ,vermicelli, fresh veggie food.
I tried stir fry with pork and it was very delicious at a good price!
Great but not best. Worth to wait and try on your own

author_name: Chiang Mai Travel all U need is LOVE
review_text: *Pros: - 40-60thb/bowl - super tasty! - fresh ingredients! - fast servings! *Cons: - None, all U need is LOVE! #chiangmaitravelalluneedislove #supportsmallbusiness #ilovechiangmai #SEOchiangmai #BTLmarketingChiangMai #GoogleMarketing #betterwebtraffic
Had both the soup and dry version... Prefer the dry version as it's more flavorful... Very systematic ordering system, just order, pay, and wait for your number to be called.
Delicious street food in Chiang Mai. (queue for 15-30 minutes)
love this shop so much.I cannot miss this place when I visit CNX. I recommend the extra Pork Stir Fried Suki. During this time , you don't have to wait that long que.
The suki is delicious. Everything need to scan throughout mobile phone. The food is very fast serving.
Fry Sukiyaki Seafood very good, well organize with queue system üëçüëçüëç
Very delicious but long queue:(. Worth to wait.

A typical tasty suki. *Recommended to get QueueQ app and get in the queue first for shorter wait time* Can try if you aren‚Äôt in a hurry and can wait. They serve super tender pork. Viscous noodle. The sauce is too spicy for me, and without the sauce, it‚Äôs pretty tasteless. The best part is the smell from the pan that stays on the food.
Popular thai style suki in Chiangmai. Tender beef with fresh and crisp veggie.
Love it! It was hard to find parking there.
Super yummy! I love the burnt wok aroma and crispy veggies. -1 one star just because i had to wait almost an hour for the Suki
Cheap and aroi makk grilled Pork Ball on skewers! 8 skewers for 40 baht!
Best Thai suki long queue but it mostly take fewer 15 mins to wait for a table
THE BEST SUKI IN THAILAND HANDS DOWN. Stayed in Chiangmai a week and came back here again and again. SO YUMMY.

Honestly not good. First of all you have to wait 1-2 hours to get a seat which is fine (we have no problem with waiting) but then you expect the food to be really good. Was it good? No. Tasteless and nothing special. A lot of other places offer much better food. So why there is a hype around this place is a mystery. Don‚Äôt waste your time waiting for a chance to eat cause tastewise it is literally not even 5 out of 10. Gets 1 star for the whole experience.
Hands down the best food I had in Chiang-Mai. There's always a line, so come early and add extra noodles and toppings if you eat a lot. You can't go wrong with this place.
Good sukiyaki thai style with vegetarian option
Long line but worth the wait. Tried both the soup and stir fry. Will go back again tomorrow!
Not recommend at all. Worst suki sauce ever!

Went on Friday evening 6+pm. There were 10 numbers ahead of us. Spent 15 minutes for our number to be called and another 15 minutes to wait for our food. It's definitely worth the wait if you have the time. The suki sauce is like the Singapore yong tau fu (niang dou fu) sauce mixed with chilli sauce. The combination of the ÁôΩËèú,ÂÜ¨Á≤â,Ëõã and the stirr frying time/heat is simply to perfection!
Recommended to us and didn‚Äôt disappoint. 50 Baht per person and better than some meals which cost way more. About 10 minutes wait between arriving and eating. We had chicken stir fry.

Utmost disappointment. Quality has gone down during the last few years. Their dry sukiyaki used to have a great wok hei with slightly charred ingredients. Now the greens are a mixture of wilted and undercooked. It seems that the place has become a victim of its own success. Others seems to love it, as the queues have become over 1 hour long at times.

Food was lovely, ordered the Store Fried Noodles with Pork, there was an hour queue to be seated or an allocated number ticket system for take away (we got take away and sat on a bench near by) Been around for ages and people keep coming back, so they must be doing something right. Adam 34 üá¨üáß

You have to wait for a queue to sit and that because they offer a very good food and this place is very popular. The food are serve hot and should finish them before it's get cold. Best for street food atmosphere. You can find paid parking lot on the alley.

Foreigners - Ask for the queue device at the cashier. It will buzz when the table is ready for you. No need to stand in the queue. The stir fried one was delicious although a bit too oily for me. Still recommended. The fish was alright. Fast service considering how many people (and food delivery men) are queing up.
Best suki in Thailand. Don't miss. Local price but tasty. Vegetables are fresh!

Worth waiting for about 30mins plus 20mins for the dish! Suki with pork looks simple but it's so tasty. It does go very well with the sauce. I can smell wok-charred even they cooked about 40 seconds per dish!
Perfect evening snack. 60THB for nice Stir fry and drink.
My first visit was amazing but little miss on my second visit. Seafood suki to be preferred!
Arrive early and/or use the QueQ app to avoid long wait times.
Absolutely fantastic. I had the mixed seafood, which was excellent with the right amount of spice and lots of veg. The pork was 6/5.

They do give a good amount for 55 baht. This brought the rating up to a 3 star. Taste is average, but very salty. I love suki and eat it often. Service here is horrible and if you order take away you just have to stand outside on the concrete and wait. It took 30 min to get a bowl of suki. This could be a great place again if managment would start managing the service they give.

Decided to try when we see the long Q, figured it can't be bad. Pork and chicken slices v tender. Stir fry veg has wok hei. Best combi is meat, stir fry..tried seafood broth nothing special, similar to seafood hor fun gravy. Waited 1hr to get a table, number then was 31, my Tix was 58. Go walk around, try the other foods at night mkt whilst waiting. u place order and pay once your number is called, they tell u your table number. Waited another 15min for food after seated. IMO, it's ok, nice but not worth queuing 1+hr for.
I have a stir-fried suki with pork, a bit oily but tastes good. Due to I come in weekdays evening, there is no waiting line. Suitable for those who are looking for late night comfort food.

Excellent sukis, still with reasonnable prices. I love their dry seafood sukis. Unfortunately, it is very popular now and you have to wait a long time to be seated and half an hour standing for take away. Not enough place to add more cooks. I still find it is the best sukis with an incomparable slightly spicy sauce (you do not have to add it if you do not like it spicy).
Very tasty and well organized food stall.
Long wait 1:30 hr. If you in a hurry order take away wait 30 min. The taste is good. Price is reasonable. Order fast come early because it may ran out of ingredient.
- Not delicious as expected. - Waiting queue is about 2-3 hours.

I had a great experience and meal here. First went to the Cowboy Hat Pork Leg Rice stall next door and then walked over here for some suki. Was the best suki I've had so far in Thailand. Needed to wait about 15 mins for a table but was worth it. Price was 60 baht for a bowl and highly recommended.

Be very careful and make sure you smell the meat prior to eating. I got food poisoning from the beef and egg noodle here! Was a very bad experience. Was up all night sick and missed my tour the next morning.
Best suki in town, make sure you try it at least once during the trip!
Best suki in Thailand hands down. Recommend if you don‚Äôt want to wait the line just order take away and it will be much faster.

One of the Best Sukiyakis i have eaten in Thailand. The suki pork (moo) without soup is defently the best one. Suki seafood with soup was Not that good. But the suki moo without soup is one of the best i ate in my Life. The pork meat is so juicy and really delicious. One Star less, bc you need to get a Ticket and wait really Long until it is your Turn. So better come Here earlier and get a Tickets BC it can Take Up to 1h until its your Turn.
The taste is ordinary. Ordering is quite difficult. Long wait. Not recommended.
Cheap, fast, and good vermicilli that can either be stir-fry or soup. Has vegetables and egg inside. Basically authentic thai street food. About 55 baht (USD1.6) a bowl

I ate this restaurant first time in 2010. until now still really feel good the same with the taste and mood when I get there. (different only wait more time haha) but it worth, fair price, local guy also eat this place.
Things I love are the cabbage which is very crunchy and delicious tender pork. A little too sweet suki sauce. Booking from Qque application so dont have to wait for too long.

Over rated and exaggerated, hence now no longer patrons friendly. They need competitors. Telling patrons it takes long to dine there and also moderately long to pack, you get the feel that they do not want your business. Potentially, when their demands drop, things will changed.
Sooo good.. midnight snack and go back to north gate
The best Thai dish in Chang mai
Taste good but long waiting time
The best Suki I have had in Thailand and at a very reasonable price. There was a queue to get a seat due to the popularity, but it was well worth it!
There are some great food options here every day (I think it‚Äôs everyday). The Sukiyaki(?) stand is always packed with Thai and Farang alike. Highly recommend this smaller dinner market.

The worst experience in Thailand, the staffs were extremely rude. The seat can only sit if you get food, otherwise you can only stand there and wait. We didn't know at first that after we sat down, they asked us to leave with some insulting gestures, they ruined all our moods on the last day of our tour.
The food is good. Take away portions have been reduced to almost half. Still hungry, not satisfied.

Not my favourite food market in CM. Too busy, crowded, dirty, always a wet floor, some bad smells and poorly arranged stalls. Some good food to be found but there are many many other great places to eat....don't be a sheep, find your own favourite place to eat.
Super yummy Thai style sukiyaki. The price is reasonable. Beef sukiyaki is 50 baht. If they have English menu it should help a lot of tourist to order.

This place claims the name "Coca", actually they are not the real Coca,just copied the name,shame. The food is so so and the service is very poor, they are arrogant. Do the customers ask them to eat for free??? The owner is Tomboy,so arrogant,her girlfriend is not beautiful and she has very bad manners to customers.
Absolutely local spot to dine yummy soupy goodness. Expect a queue. Not recommended when it rains.

Visited on a food tour booked online. Very varied and interesting options. We greatly benefitted from having an actual tour guide however so if you're unfamiliar with what something is, it's best to look up names of dishes, or ask if the shop keep had a menu with English translation.
Off the hook! Fresh crisp cabbage, succulent beef, friendly service. Some English helped with getting the table and understanding wait time...worth the wait (20 Min on busy night)!!!
this is most delicious suki ever
Another famous food stall at the Changpuek Market. The stir-fry suki was done super well: fragrant, flavorful, fresh off the wok, stir-fried to perfection.

If you are tired of Northern food and want to try Thailand's street food, this is a place to be in Chiangmai. Price starts at around 2 USD. Beef Suki Hang (stir fry vermicelli and beef insuki sauce) is a must try.
Fantastic stir fry of glass noodle with pork and seafood. Loved the crunchiness of the semi raw lettuce. Flavorful but not overwhelming.
Isn't really worth the hype. The food is alright but nothing special compared to neighboring stalls and definitely not worth the 20 minute wait.
Best suki in town. Fresh vegetables, well seasoned glass noodles, stir fried with egg and your choice of protein! Must try!!!
Simple and full of flavor. Do not miss.
This was literally the BEST thing we ate on our entire trip in Thailand!! So so good.
I had the stir fried noodles. It is good but does not worth the long queue.
Food is good but got the bad smell from drain tube. Need to hurry eat and go
Delicious food with small serving. Very cheap so not complaining. Mouth watering duck...
Good but honestly it doesn't taste as good as its reputation promises. Maybe they were good in the past and let the ball drop with the fame
It‚Äôs like one serving of Chinese steamboat in a plate. A pleasant one with delicious sauce. Pleasantly tasty to the most fussy tongue.
Very popular (rightly) street food. Cheap and delicious. See photo for how to write your order.
Very nice place So much choice and food options Reasonable price
It has to spare time for waiting at least 1 hr. If you hurry to go , forget this dish .
The best Suki Haeng I've ever had, thank you so much for the great service and delicious food. Thanks Mark Wiens for the tip!
Quick and cheap place to grab a decent meal.
I don‚Äôt get the hype here. Had a long waiting time and the taste was not that great. Maybe I got a bad batch.
I took a late night walk and stumbled across this market. Great food and many options to select from.
Absolute banging, don't judge a book by its covers. The locals eat here for a reason, smashed it.
Best Suki in chiang mai, a visit is a must but need to wait at least 20 mins for a table ü§£üëç
Authentic local feel! Food is good too!
Long queue even after 22:30. Valuable meals.
long waiting time. no parking space. taste good. good price.
Always busy but one of the best places to get suki in Chiang Mai
Love their beef egg noodles soup...cheap food...cute waitress that keeps her smile..üòâ
A local Suki at Chiang Mai, delicious
Reasonable price for the greatest fried sukiyaki in town, and in Thailand.
Delicious as always. Open in the evening. Good managed.
Great location with a few food stalls, try the the one that has duck!
A mouthful of fun. A simple treat that compliments the evening market.
The best Suki in Chiang Mai. Delicious
It's not real sukiyaki, but it's fuxking good.
Pretty good food really nice staff
Got shaved by the devil, nice and clean job
ITS NOT OPEN ON MONDAY PLS UPDATE
Great food. Try the kaew ka moo
I love this place. Suki heng moo all the way.
One of the best THAI STYLE SUKIIII!!!
A couple of good options for food and drinks
Pretty alright. Staff is a bit slow.
The best of Suki sterfry in the world!!
they are really rude to customers
